{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_kaffirlily_ver01/data/sn82007637/00340580370/1945110901/0016.xml":{"full_text":"Page Two\nTrizHiait Keynotes\nL-M Conference\nContinued From Page Ono\nfingers on the causes of labor\nunrest when they emphasized\nthe yet-unresolved question of\nWage-price relations. Again\nbringing up the \u201cpeople\u201d versus\nthe \u201clabor\u201d angle. Truman\nWarned that, \u201cif the people do\npot find the answers here (in\nthe L-M Conference), they will\nfind them some place else.\u201d\nTruman assailed jurisdictional\nstrikes, but said, \u201cOn the other\nhand, management too often has\nipoked upon labor relations as a\nStepchild of\ndisregarded\nyersy has\nWhere real\nfng becomes very difficult.\u201d\nits business, to be\nuntil the contro\nreached a point\ncollective bargain-\nWallace walloped hard on the\ntheme that, \u201cIn the present sit\nuation, incomes of wage earners\nare declining and, unless a sub\nstantial increase in wage rates is\ngranted, this decline will con\ntinue into 10461.\u201d\nFavors Wage Raise\nWallace insisted that, \u201cTf we\nmaintain levels of production\nand wage income and effective\npurchasing demand levels\nanywhere near approaching full\nemployment there are clear\nIndications that basic wage rates\nean be raised substantially in\nmany industries without gen\nerally increased prices and with\nout impairment of the profit\nposition.\u201d Unless this is done,\nhe continued, \u201cthe contrast be\ntween profits and other forms of\nincome would generally be so\nextreme that business quickly\nWould incur public disfavor.\nCIO President Murray de\nclared that \u201cI have become con\nvinced by the events of recent\nmonths that there has been a\nsteady deterioration of indus\ntrial relationships in this coun\ntry since V-E Day. Today we are\nconfronted with a major col\nlapse in labor-management re\nlations.\u201d\nother\nthat,\nbased\nThe CIO head joined\nspeakers in underscoring\n\u201cA determined approach\nUpon the genuine and\nhearted acceptance of collective\nbargaining by labor and man\nagement is of the essence in our\ndemocratic society.\"\nWorkers Left Stranded\n\"Our\nMurray argued that,\ntrue problem is the little word\n\u2018No\u2019 which has been the re\nsponse of too much of industry\nto wage increase demands. The\nshifting tides of our economy\nhave left workers stranded,\u201d he\nsaid, \u201cdeeply mindful of the\nbrutal depressions of past eras,\neager to achieve for their fam\nilies and for the nation a\u2019a a\n\u2022tXx\u00ab\npi-1\nW\nJ:\nit\ntv-\n^4\nwhole that economic stability\nand purchasing power which\ncharacterizes the healthy, prosp\nerous economy. At the very time\nwhen history has cast collective\nbargaining in such a critical\nrole, at the very time when it\ncan yield the most for the com\nmon good, it has been rejected\nby so many American employ\ners.\u201d\nAFL President Green, in a\npointed speech, asserted that\n\u201cLabor\u2019s basic right to organize\nand bargain collectively and the\nfull acceptance of that right by\nlhe employers stands side by\nside with the right of employers\nto manage their enterprise and\ndirect its operation without in\nterference.\u201d\nWhen labor-management dis\nputes cannot be resolved, con\nciliation presents \u201cthe first ef\nfective and tested step toward\nthe settlement of differences,\u201d\nGreen said. He recommended\nimprovement and modernization\nof the U. S. Conciliation Service,\nwhich he characterized as one\nof the most democratically con\nstituted agencies of the gov\nernment.\nTurning to compulsory arbi\ntration which many anti-union\nemployers and industry groups\nhave advocated, the AFL presi\ndent charged flatly that \u201cArbi\ntration fails if it is based upon\ncompulsion. Compulsory arbi\ntration has not worked\npast and will not work\nfuture.\u201d\nWants Grmind Rules\nin\nin\nthat at\nSchwel lenbach found\nthe war\u2019s end both labor and\nindustry were \"rather rusty\u201d in\nthe techinques of collective bar\ngaining. Therefore, he said,\n\u201cwe felt that if collective bar\ngaining was to have a fair\nchance to fiuceed it Was neces\nsary that representatives of in\ndustry and labor meet together\nin order that they might lay\ndown and define the ground\nrules under which collective\nbargaining would operate.\u201d\nAfter this remark about collec\ntive bargaining, however, the\nLabor Secretary tried to impress\nthe two delegations that \u2018\u2018you\nare not here representing your\nindividual industry or union.\u201d\nThe delegates were attending,\nhe said, repeating President\nTruman, because they were\nAmerican citizens.\n\u201cEar too often,\u201d Sehwefien\nbach said, \u201clocal union stewards\nand officers have failed to fol\nlow the grievance procedure\noutlined In their contracts and\nhave struck plants in violation\nof grievance procedures. This\npractice must stop or labor will\ndo great injury to itself.\u2019\u2019 Indus\ntrialists, whom labor has re\npeatedly charged with the\nabandoment or deliberate dis\nruption of grievance machinery,\nwere slapped on the wrist with\nthe remark that \u201cTop manage\nment during the war has been\nncllned to devote hut little time\no active participation in labor\nproblems.\u201d\nStrikers Accuse\nA&P Management\nContinued From Page One\nlow standard of living upon our\ncommunity. This ja calculated\nto discourage the strikers\nnow are more determined\never that A&P must raise\nwages and sign the same\nwarehouses, or\nwhere it takes\ntake its business\nits money.\u201d\nWants To Know\n...i\nMr. Steinberg\ni\nITS\nCola\nwho\nthan\ntheir\ncon-\nfarther said\n\u201cwe are not impressed with lhe\nA&P threat. In fact, the town\nvsould he betier nff without an\noutfit that attempts to lower the\nliving standards of a large sec\ntion of this community. I might\nsay that we know of a large\nchain which would like to come\ninto Toledo if th? A de\ncides to leave. We would like\nto know if A wants to move\nso we can bring in another\nchain which pays decent living\nwages. A&P certainly isn\u2019t a\nnecessity to this town. We can\nget along without them and\nbring in a progressiva company\nto take their place\nAuthoritative reports have\nreached the TOLEDO UNION\nJOURNAL that a large Concern\nhas been in Toledo looking over\nthe area and have conferred\nwith labor heads, public offi\ncials and business men relative\nto the advisability of moving in.\nNo meetings have taken place\nbetween the company manage\nment and the Union end none\nare in sight according to Mr.\nSteinberg Meanwhile, the strike\ncontinues with 500 emloyees out\nof work as a consequence.\nM3 Makes Sense!\nM\u2019RINGFIELD, III. (LPA)\u2014\nPockets already severely\npinched between the high cost,\nof living and the too slowly\nthawing vage freeze should be\nlax free, the Illinois State Fede,\nration contended last week Al\nits annual convention, tiifM^rmip\nrecommended that inco taxes\nbe epmjnated on ann\nder i)00.\nWatched yian\nThe eyes of the entire indus\ntrial and labor world are fo\ncused on Walter Reuther and\n350,000 General Motors work\ners, under his leadership, who\nare fighting the nation\u2019s rich\nest corporation for a 30% pay\nraise. If Reuther, vice-presi\ndent of the United Auto Work\ners-( IO, succeeds in negotiat\ning the pay hike it will set the\npace for dozens of other in\ndustries and hring raises to\nmillions in every field.\nVoters Defeat\nAll Issues\u2014\nElect Grzezinski\nthe\nthe\nContinued From Page One\nissue up was not disclosed\nPAC officers.\nDefeat Increased Term\nlie\nrr pay un-\nP^\u00a3SCR\n1ONS\nObtainable\nMatla(*ra4 PhtraiMlrti\nC\u00abMR\u00abU\u00abt\nUNDT Co*\nboratorier\n\u00abl\nThe\nPres\nipftOrt\nMONSOt\nUAW\nby\nAlso defeated was the amend\nment to the city charter which\nwould have increased the terms\nof city councilman to four years.\nThis amendment which was op\nposed 'by the PAC was snowed\nunder to the tune of 13,087 for\nwhile 39,804 were against the\nproposal.\nAlso voted on in Tuesday elec\ntion were members of the school\nboard and city councilmen. The\nthree who were elected to the\nschool board include Edward C.\nAmes, William C. Sanzenbacher\nand Fred A. Hunt. Hunt and\nAmes are incumbents. It will\nbe Sanzenbacher\u2019s first term.\nPR Count Thursday\nex\nPR\nBoard of Election officials\npressed the belief that the\ncount for city councilrnen would\nbe able to get under way\nWednesday morning. Actual\ncounting of the vole probably\nwill be delayed until late\nWednesday afternoon or Thurs\nday morning due to the amount\nof time required to scan for in\nvalid ballots.\nThe quota for this year\u2019s elec\ntion will run higher than any\nsince 1939. To secure election\nunder the PR system, the candi\ndates must secure 10 per cent of\nthe vote plus one. In .1043, there\nwere 64,600 valid votes.\nPolitical observers around the\nrlty were predicting that Tom\nBurke would not run better than\nfourth, the same as two years\nago. They point out that labor\u2019s\nfailure to defeat the PR system\nof electing city councilmen indi\ncates that the labor vote was not\nas large as had been previously\nexpected.\nPoint to Grzezinski\nAnother school of thought be\nlieves that Burke will run strong\nbecause of the showing made by\nlabor in elevating Judge Stanley\nA. Grzezinski despite the efforts\nmade during the campaign by\nCouncilman Ollie Czelusta to de\nfeat him by claiming that can\ndidates for public office who\nhave Polish names could not be\nelected except under the PR\nsystem.\nActual completion of the total\nPR vote will probably not be\nmade until next week.\nFull\nEmployment\nBill Stalled\n('ontinued From Page One\nready the Senate version of the\nlaw was seriously weakened be\nfore it was approved.\nThe desperate need for im\nmediate action by Congress was\nunderscored by a report released\nby the United States Employ\nment Service. Director Robert\nC. Goodwin disclosed that \u201cre\nports from all parts of the nation\n\u00bbhow that September was a\nHINDSIGHT\nContinued From Page Ona\nEven the silly statement made by Councilman Ollie\nC'zelusta, that a candidate of Polish extraction could not\nhe elected except under the PR system was knocked into\nthe ashcan by the voters at last Tuesday\u2019s election, proof\nsufficient that the best argument the voters of Toledo\nhave is their right to upset the applecart and make it hard\non thos\u00ab who now must pay for their repudiated leader\nship.\nIn conclusion, we wish to adopt tho words of the\nfamous naval hero who said,\nfight.\u201d\nTH! TOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nBefore Dawn\nohg ohehI\n4\njl__\ninreatens I\nTo Sue OPA\nISnyder\n_.Favors\nj. p_.\nIbis CIO picket gel up LzatiOn, wages, prices, and other\nbefore dawn to join the line I\n9f strikers around the Kelsey- vltal reconversion questions.\nHayes Wheel Co. in Detroit. [Snyder\u2019s recommendations carry\nThe month-long strike of the lall the weight of White House\nUnited Auto Workers-CIO [pronouncements in most cases.\ndrew union eh.r,M that th. production muat b. r\u201e3\u00ab|,\nworkers were being given I Jf x. x.\nrunaround by management. [and distribution of peacetime\nI nion griveances that started [goods must be expanded as\nthe walkout are still unsettled, [quickly as possible, Snyder said.\nTflk \"Fl* __\nBy\nNEW YORK (LPA)\u2014Sig\ni Inificant statements on a na\ntional policy that sounded\n(amazingly like the position of\n[organized labor were made in\nla series of speeches here and In\nNew England by Reconversion\nDirector Snyder last week.\nSnyder\u2019s statements were\nconsidered especially significant\nsince he is the man who has the\nfinal say on questions of admin\nlistration policy covering stabil-\n|lf this is done, industry should\nbe able to absorb any costs\n[caused by raising wages to make I\nI up for the loss in overtime pav\nContinued From Page One I\n,x Iwith the end of war production.\nOPA the union would bring