te contend\ned that \u201cIt is saddening to see\nlast Tuesday\u2019s |how many business men scoff\nwill be called |at tbe ifiFa employment.\niThey view with Olympian calm\nthe prospect of millions unem\nployed. If this country is ever\ndestroyed, it will not be by for\neign enemies, but by destitulioo____\nFor the well-being of the na\ntion, the headstrong power of\nmanagement must be restricted\u201d\nPointing out that although\nsome employers have social\nvision he asserted that \u201cIt is dis\nconcerting to think that an\nalarmingly large percentage of\nemployers would like to see an\nopen labor market, a period of\nlow taxes, low wages, and high\n,..M Jprofits. Thia is practically a\nWa have just begun to Lool-proof pattern for depres\nliioru.\u201d\nReuther Demands\nReconsideration\nDETROIT, Nov. 2\u2014In view\nof President Truman\u2019s wage\nprice message to the nation\non Oct. 30, Walter P. Reuther,\nUAW-CIO vice-president and\ndirector of the General Motors\nDepartment, demanded today\nthat General Motors Corporation\nreconsider its \u201cflat rejection\u201d of\nthe UAW\u2019s 30 per cent demand\nand that C. E. Wilson, GM Presi\ndent, personally enter the nego\ntiations with the Union.\nReuther\u2019s demand was con\ntained in a letter to Wilson, in\nwhich the UAW official said.\n\u201cEvery factor cited by the\nPresident, in support of his\nstatement that \u2019wage increases\nare imperative,\u2019 applies par\nticularly to the case o\u00a3 General\nMotor Corporation.\n\u201cIn the light of the President\u2019s\nclear statement of national pol\nicy and his mandate that the\nparties \u2019must get back to free\nand fair collective bargaing,'\nReuther Baid, \u201cWill General\nMotors Corporation now recon\nsider its flat rejection of our 30\nper cent wage demand?\n\u201cWill you (Wilson) personally\nenter into negotiations with us\nin accordance with the Presi\ndent\u2019s mandate?\u201d\nReuther also sent a telegram\nto Truman, in which he said:\n\u201cWe are determined to carry\nout your directive that wage in\ncreases are imperative without\nprice increases and shall be ar\nrived at through free collective\nbargaining We again rei\nterate our pledge to the Ameri\ncan people that wage increases\nin General Motors Corporation\nwill not necessitate price in\ncreases 1\nWsge\nnacMng Economists\nWASHINGTON (LPA)\u2014Labor\u2019s wage demands re\nceived a considerable boost here last week, with the revela\ntion by a group of economists dealing directly with the White\nHouse that industry as a whole could pay a 24% wage in\ncrease adn still make stupendous profits of $6,300,000,000\nafter taxes in 1946.\nother factors may impair this\nability.\nThe figures were part of a\nreport prepared by the econom\nists in the Office of War Mobili\nzation and Reconversion for the\nOWMR\u2019s Advisory Board, which\nmet last week to discuss Admin\nistration wage policies The\nBoard advises Reconversion Di\nrector John W. Snyder, and in\ncludes leaders of labor, industry,\nfarm and civic groups appointed\nby the President.\nWhile unions assert that a\n30 basic pay increase is possi\nble while industry can still coin\nhigh profits, labor economists\nhere were quick to assert that\nthe White House report, which\n\u201cleaked\u201d to the press, substan\ntially reinforced their own very\ndetailed calculations on which\nwage negotiations in many in\ndustries are now proceeding.\nEconomists Conclusions\nHere are some of the conclu\nsions of the White House econ\nomists:\nThe take-home pay of the\naverage industrial worker in\n1946 will have 10% less pur\nchasing power, after he pays his\ntaxes, than did his earnings in\nJanuary of 1941. His weekly pay\ncheck will be down 28% with\nin a few months from wartime\nlevels.\nDeclines in costs, which can\nbe be accurately measured, will\nimprove management\u2019s ability\ntn pay wage raises, though some\nOk MA\nFriday, November 9, 1945\nDemands Receive\nCould Grant Raises -1^\nBased on these measurable de\nclines in costs, wage rate in\ncreases averaging 24% for all\nindustry could be granted due to\nthe ending of overtime, down\ngrading, and the ending of the\nexcess profits tax.\nUnemployment will reach\n8,000,000 by next spring, and\nnational output will decline\nabout 25% from $206 billion to\n$165 billion or less.\n\u201cThe behavior of the stock\nmarket in recent months,\u201d ac\ncording to OWMR economists,\n\u201csuggests that the business and\nfinancial community expect pro\nfits after taxes to remain tat or\nnear wartime peak. The market\nvalue of securities on the N. VFl\nStock Exchange has risen by a\nthird since D-Day and by 10%\nbetween V-J Day and Sept. 30,\n1945.\u201d\nI5c-An-Hour Pay Boost\nDUBUQUE, la. (LPA) \u2014Pay\nboosts up to 15c an hour have\nbeen gained by the Upholsterers\nInternational Union AFL for\nworkers at the Arkell Safety\nBag Co. here, in the second\nyearly contract negotiated since\nthe company was established two\nyears ago. Retroactive to April\n6, supply girls, shipping room\nworkers and other will benefit.\nO\ns'","height":"27039","width":"20466"}}
